To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, we use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command is typically placed just after the document's introduction.

Here is an example of a LaTeX document with a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

% Other content of the document

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction of the document.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion of the document.

\end{document}
```

In this example, `\tableofcontents` is placed where we want the table of contents to appear in the document. The table of contents will list all parts of the document that have a `\section` command, which creates a section heading. When the document is compiled, LaTeX will automatically generate the table of contents based on these section headings.

Note that the `\tableofcontents` command should be placed in the main body of the document, not in the preamble or document header. It's also generally a good idea to include a `\clearpage` command immediately following the `\tableofcontents` command to ensure that any floats (like figures or tables) are placed properly in relation to the table of contents.

