In Java, strings can be compared using either the `==` operator or the `equals()` method. However, these two approaches compare strings differently.

The `==` operator checks if the two compared objects are exactly the same object in memory. It does not compare the actual contents of the strings. This means that if you have two different string objects with the same content, `==` will return `false`.

On the other hand, the `equals()` method compares the contents of the strings. It checks if the characters in the two strings are the same, regardless of whether they are stored in the same object in memory. This means that if you have two string objects with the same content, `equals()` will return `true`.

Here's an example:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";

if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same object");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are different objects");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("The contents of str1 and str2 are the same");
} else {
    System.out.println("The contents of str1 and str2 are different");
}
```

In this example, both `==` and `equals()` will return `false` because `str1` and `str2` are different objects in memory, even though they have the same content.

In general, you should use `equals()` to compare string contents and `==` to compare object references. However, it's important to understand the difference between these two operators to avoid bugs in your code.

Here's a Java solution to the problem without using loops or recursion:

