public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n == 0) return false;
        if (n < 0) n = -n;
        int count = 0;
        while (n > 1) {
            n /= 3;
            count++;
        }
        return count != 0;
    }
}
```

Explanation:

We first check if n is zero, and if so, return false because 0 is not a power of three. If n is negative, we make it positive because -3^x is not a valid power of three.

We then use a while loop to divide n by 3 until n becomes 1. The number of iterations of the loop is equal to the power of three that n represents. If n is not a power of three, the loop will terminate when n becomes 1, and the count will be zero. If n is a power of three, the loop will terminate when n becomes 1, and the count will be equal to the exponent of three in n. We return true if the count is not zero, which means n is a power of three.

